The Committee on Freedom of Association has nonetheless given its
opinion in a general manner on the essential or non-essential nature of a series of
specific services. Thus, the Committee has considered to be essential services in the strict sense,
where the right to strike may be subject to major restrictions or even
prohibitions, to be: the hospital sector; electrical services; water supply services;
the telephone service; air traffic control. In contrast, the Committee has considered that, in general, the following do not
constitute essential services in the strict sense of the term, and therefore the
prohibition to strike does not pertain. ­ Radio and television;
­ pleasure parks;
­ the petroleum sector;
­ the metal sector;
­ ports (loading and unloading);
­ the mining sector;
­ banking;
­ transport generally;
­ agricultural activities;
­ refrigeration enterprise;
